(2) Each one might have been spe- cially assigned to look aster certain kinds of the ward’s property, or his property in some specific locality ; in this case he was, within his sphere os action, possessed of all the rights and subject to all the duties of a single guardian. (3) The administration might be undivided: in which case each had a complete right to manage the ward's affairs subject to his eolleagues’ right of veto, and the liability was joint throughout, even where loss was occasioned by the act or omission of a single member.

When inferior magistrates appointed tutors or curators to persons whose fortunes fell below a certain minimum (Tit. 20. 4 supr.)‚ they did so sine inquisitione, and therefore were bound to make the selected per- son give satisdatio in the usual manner. If they exacted insufficient security, they were made liable in person for all loss resulting from their negligence by a senatusconsult of Trajan, Cod. 5. 75. 5, and this liability was extended to their heirs by Antoninus Pius, Dig. 27. 8. 6.
